2":"1192","1170":"1170","1205":"1205","1148":"1148","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1169":"1169","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","environ 1205":"about 1205","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Semur-en-Brionnais, Charolles, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France":"Charolles, Charolles, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France","Palestine, Palestine":"Palestine","Burgundy, France":"Burgundy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bourgogne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile.","Americanized form of French   Bourgoin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourgoin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphee, Alyre, Andre, Armand, Aurore, Celina, Emile, Gilberte, Jacques, Laurent, Lucienne, Olivier.","French:","variant of <b>Bourgouin</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a habitational name for someone from Burgundy (Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>), a region of eastern France having Dijon as its center. The area was invaded by the <i>Burgundii</i>, an ancient Germanic tribe from whom it takes its name, in about  AD  480. The duchy of Burgundy, created in 877 by Charles II, King of the Western Franks, was extremely powerful in the 